text: I told my friend I was learning Spanish; he said, "So, you're taking a siesta from English?"
Jose said he'd do anything for a living, so I was surprised when he became a mime and said nothing at all.
I invested in a revolutionary new product that makes you invisible, but I can't see any profits.
My dog started a Ponzi scheme; he calls it "Bark Madoff."
My gym trainer told me to strike a pose, so I hit the mannequin; now I'm banned from the yoga class.
I caught my mirror looking at itself in another mirror; talk about being self-absorbed.
Spencer's so optimistic, if he fell in a vat of boiling water, he'd probably shout, "Spa day!"
I bought a silk shirt that said 'one size fits all,' but when I tried it on, it was more like 'one size fits moth.'
I tried a scheme to work out and watch TV at the same time; it's called "Netflix and treadmill."
Why did Spencer bring a ladder to the bar? He heard the drinks were on the house.
My silk pajamas are like a bad joke; they always seem to slip away when you need them the most.
I wrote a book on revolutionary movements; it's a real page-turner, mostly because the pages keep trying to overthrow the cover.
I told Spencer to play dead in our acting class; he must be a method actor because he's still not moving.
Why don't Spanish football teams get cold? Because they always have plenty of fans!
I bought a two-way mirror; it's great, but I can never tell if it's me or my FBI agent who looks better in the morning.
My therapist told me to act my age, not my shoe size; jokes on her, they're the same number.
What's a fish's favorite instrument? The reef-er.
I tried to restore my computer to an earlier date, but it just sent me a calendar invite for 1995.
I asked the IT guy how to restore my faith in humanity, and now I have a new antivirus.
They say in a world of infinite possibilities, every choice matters; meanwhile, I'm still trying to decide between "paper" or "plastic."
They say every snowflake is unique, which makes me wonder if they also have trouble finding a date for Friday night.
Tried to restore my vintage car to its original state, but it just asked me for leaded gasoline and a cassette tape.
I started a Spanish pun band called "The Juan Hit Wonders." Our first single? "Livin' La Vida Loca-tive Case."
My yoga instructor said to embrace the impossible, so I hugged my in-laws and now we need a miracle.
Why don't PlayStations ever get lonely? Because they have too many fans.
Why did the comedian wear a silk suit to his gig? Because he wanted his punchlines to be smooth.
I tried to play hide and seek in Milan, but with all the fashion models around, it was more like hide and chic.
Katie tried to catch fog yesterday, now she's mist.
Why did the algae and the coral get married? They had a lichen for each other on the reef.
I asked a historian for a revolutionary joke, but he just gave me a long-winded explanation of the French Revolution – the punchline never came.
I heard about a mathematician who became a writer; he had a great plot, but the story didn't add up.
I told my wife she was drawing her eyebrows too high. She looked surprised.
My PlayStation must be a politician; it promises high performance but always ends up freezing at the worst times.
I'd tell you a chemistry joke but I know I wouldn't get a reaction.
Why don't they play poker in Milan? Too many people are trying to fold.
I'm reading a book on anti-gravity. It's impossible to put down.
I asked the fish if he liked his new home on the reef; he said it was "sub-lime."
I told my girlfriend I was cheating on her with my PlayStation. She laughed until she saw my high score in "The Sims: Love Triangle Edition."
I bought a belt in Milan. It's now the most committed relationship I have – it's literally attached to my waist.
They said the scheme was foolproof, but they didn’t account for me being an overachiever.
Why don't printers ever win at sports? Because they always seem to lose their drivers.
I told my printer to print on both sides to save paper, but it just flipped out.
Why don't secret agents use printers? Because they always seem to spill the beans in the output tray.
I told my friend I had a plot of land, and he asked if it was any good for a story. I said, "Sure, if you like tales with a lot of dirt."
The plot of my last relationship was like a mystery novel—turns out the clues were there, she was just not that into me.
Katie bought a boat and named it "Relation"; now she can say she's in a stable relationship.
I asked my friend if he felt mature at 30, and he said, "Absolutely, I've even got a separate drawer for my Legos now."
I told my mirror I was seeing someone else on the side, it shattered.
I have a joke about construction, but I'm still working on it.
My computer sent me an invitation to update software at the most inconvenient time – it must have learned from my friends.
Why did Katie sit on the clock? She wanted to be on time for once!
Why did Jose bring a ladder to the bar? He heard the drinks were on the house.
The fundamental rule of gravity is what goes up must come down, but my stocks didn't get the memo.
I tried to act mature at the wine tasting, but then I asked for a straw.
I downloaded an anti-procrastination app, and it's great – I'll tell you how it works tomorrow.
I was invited to a pessimist's birthday party; the card said, "Don't bother bringing gifts, it's not like anything's going to make me happy."
I told my computer I needed a break, and it said it would love one too, right after installing the next 47 updates.
I told my computer I needed a break, and now it won't stop sending me Kit-Kat ads.
I downloaded a joke book, but all the punchlines were missing; it was the ultimate setup.
I asked my toaster to update its firmware, but now it just keeps burning the message "404 Bread Not Found."
I was invited to a mime's wedding, but I'm not going; I heard the vows are silent and the arguments are invisible.
My cardiologist has a great sense of humor; he always says, "A change of heart is just one bypass away."
I bought a talking doll that was supposed to mimic me, but all it says is "I need to charge my phone."
Parallel lines have so much in common. It’s a shame they’ll never meet.
I asked Jose if he could make me a burrito, but he rolled his eyes instead of the tortilla.
My fitness app said "good job" after I installed it, and I thought, "Wow, that's the most exercise I've done all week."
My drone's firmware update was supposed to improve its flight, but now it just hovers around asking for Wi-Fi passwords.
My e-reader got a firmware update and now it thinks it's a paperback, it keeps trying to dog-ear its own corners.
I bought a heart-shaped bed for our anniversary; it's not broken, just two singles pushed together.
The gentle breeze was so considerate, it avoided the wind chimes to not disturb the silence.
They say you can't die from a broken heart, but that's not what my life insurance agent told me.
I tried to play a tile-laying game with a chameleon, but he kept blending in with the bathroom floor.
I told my girlfriend she was the fundamental theorem of calculus because she's integral to my life, but she went off on a tangent.
Why did the number 7 get so upset at the party? Because it couldn't deal with everyone else being in a division.
My bookshelf came with an e-reader app installed; it's the first time I've seen a shelf reading its own books.
I heard about a new eco-friendly rock band; they only play recycled hits.
I tried to explain the fundamentals of electricity to my friend, but it was shocking how little resistance he showed to learning.
I told my friend I was starting a business recycling broken marionettes... no strings attached.
I asked the librarian if the books about telepathy were any good, she just smiled and said, "You tell me."
I tried to make a computer laugh, but it had a tough firewall against my puns.
I saw a chicken wearing a crown and thought, "Well, that's a new pecking order."
I tried to download the entire Internet, but I didn't have enough space – I guess you could say it was a bit too "web-weight."
My math teacher told me I was average; it was mean, but at least it wasn't a division.
I told my friend I was striking out with dating, but on the bright side, I've got a perfect bowling score.
I tried to play gentle music for my plants, but they grew up to be a little too vine and dandy.
I caused a stir at the bakery by asking for a self-rising cake; they handed me yeast and told me to encourage it emotionally.
Why did the dentist become a king? Because he was already skilled at crowning.
I made a timeline of my gym attendance, but it's more like a dotted line.
I told my friend I was cutting down on waste by only flushing once a day; now he's avoiding my dinner invitations.
I tried to eat a crown once, but it's harder to digest absolute power than I thought.
I watched a magician make his car disappear, and I thought, "Now that's an illusion of grand theft auto."
Why was the computer cold at the party? It left its Windows open.
I told my math book to stop being so divisive, but it just gave me more problems.
I placed a bid on a broken metronome; I won, but I still can't keep time.
Why don't secrets last long in a computer? Because it's hard to keep anything from leaking when there's so much RAMbling.
I caused a ruckus in the library by rearranging the books; turns out, people aren't fans of alphabetical disorder.
I caused a commotion at the zoo by calling the peacocks "fashion chickens"; the birds were flattered, but the chickens felt underdressed.
I won a bid for a vintage calendar; it's days are numbered.
I learned a trick to avoid ever losing my keys again—unfortunately, it doesn't work if you lose the instructions.
I said to my therapist, "I feel invisible," and she said, "Who said that?"
I acquired a bakery in a breadwinning deal, but now I'm rolling in dough and can't get out.
I told my friend I have a belt that can travel through time, but it was just a waist of time.
My therapist suggested I find my inner child, but now I'm banned from the playground.
I got a boomerang for my birthday, it's great – I can't seem to get rid of it no matter how hard I try.
I tried to trace my family tree on a timeline, but it turned out to be a cactus – everyone's a little prickly about their age.
I mastered the trick of sleeping with my eyes open during meetings—it's a real eye-opener.
I wanted to learn about acquisitions, so I started with a puzzle – unfortunately, the pieces took over my entire living room.
My therapist told me to be more assertive, so I billed her for the last session.
I made a bid on a boomerang, it was the best return on investment I ever had.
I asked the soldier if he enjoyed playing the trumpet, but he said he's more into arms than brass.
Why don't teddy bears ever finish their dinner? Because they're always stuffed!
I told my friend I'm great at laying tile, but when he saw my work, he said it was a mosaic-take.
They say love is a battlefield, which explains why Cupid comes armed with arrows instead of chocolates.
I accepted that life gives you lemons, but I'm still trying to figure out who's accepting lemonade.
I told my friend I was getting into arm wrestling, and he said, "Sounds like you're taking up arms in a very hands-on way."
Why did the tile break up with the grout? It needed more space.
I joined a protest to fight against laziness, but we all just ended up taking a stand by sitting down.
I accepted my fate as a forgetful person when I found my missing glasses on my head... for the third time today.
I told my sofa I was accepting its lumps and all, but it still gave me no support in return.
My friend's into hostile acquisitions; he just stole my pizza and called it a merger.
